{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"26c962f9-65f7-4cde-aef0-398f48588c85","content":"\n\nIn .NET MAUI, those `Application`-level overrides moved to the **`Window`** lifecycle. Override `CreateWindow` in your `App` class and hook the events:\n\n```csharp\n// App.xaml.cs\nprotected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)\n{\n    var window = base.CreateWindow(activationState);\n\n    window.Created  += (s, e) => { /* OnStart equivalent  */ };\n    window.Stopped  += (s, e) => { /* OnSleep equivalent  */ };\n    window.Resumed  += (s, e) => { /* OnResume equivalent */ };\n    window.Destroying += (s, e) => { /* cleanup            */ };\n\n    return window;\n}\n```\n\nAlternatively, subclass `Window` and override the methods directly:\n\n```csharp\npublic class MyWindow : Window\n{\n    public MyWindow(Page page) : base(page) { }\n\n    protected override void OnCreated()    { /* OnStart  */ }\n    protected override void OnStopped()    { /* OnSleep  */ }\n    protected override void OnResumed()    { /* OnResume */ }\n    protected override void OnDestroying() { /* cleanup  */ }\n}\n```\n\n**Key mapping:**\n| Xamarin.Forms | .NET MAUI Window |\n|---|---|\n| `OnStart()` | `Created` / `OnCreated()` |\n| `OnSleep()` | `Stopped` / `OnStopped()` |\n| `OnResume()` | `Resumed` / `OnResumed()` |\n\nThe shift reflects MAUI's multi-window support — lifecycle is now per-window rather than per-application.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"9bf42886-e8c8-4a44-848a-63d6dd6affd8","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about migrating lifecycle events from Xamarin.Forms to .NET MAUI. This is a knowledge question I can answer directly.\n\nIn Xamarin.Forms, you'd override `OnStart()`, `OnSleep()`, and `OnResume()` in your `Application` subclass.\n\nIn .NET MAUI, the equivalent is to use the `Window` lifecycle events or the `ILifecycleEventHandler` approach. Specifically:\n\n- MAUI still has `Application` class but the lifecycle is now handled through `Window` events or by creating a custom `Window` and overriding lifecycle methods.\n\nActually, let me be more precise. In .NET MAUI:\n\n\nThe `Application` class no longer has `OnStart`, `OnSleep`, and `OnResume` overrides like Xamarin.Forms did. Instead, you hook into the `Window` class lifecycle events — `Window.Created` maps to the old `OnStart`, `Window.Resumed` replaces `OnResume`, and `Window.Stopped` replaces `OnSleep`.\n\nYou can either subclass `Window` and override its lifecycle methods, or subscribe to these events directly in your `App` class by overriding `CreateWindow()` and attaching handlers...\n\nSetting up window event handlers...","outputTokens":1013},"id":"157a217b-d257-4cc3-9869-830affc592db","timestamp":"2026-04-05T00:47:40.648Z","parentId":"38eaa534-7a33-4395-9ced-b15800c73486"}
